rest the winds being buried on all sides: you will then be able to ob- serve their great masses and 110 300 caverns as it were built of hanging rocks 3 and when a storm has gathered and the winds have filled these, they chafe with a loud roaring shut up in the clouds, and bluster 111 their dens after the fashion of wild beasts: now from this point, now from that they send their growlings through the clouds, and seeking a way out whirl about and roll together seeds of fire out of the clouds and then gather many into a mass and make them rotate in the hollow fur- naces within, until they have burst the cloud and shone forth in forked flasheS.

From this cause again yon golden colour of clear bright fire flies down with velocity to the earth: the clouds must themselves have very many seeds of fire 3 for when they are without any moisture, they are mostly of a brilliant fiame-colour. Moreover they must take in many from the sun's light, so that with good cause they are ruddy and shed forth fires. When therefore the wind has driven thrust squeezed together and col- lected into one spot these clouds, they press out and shed forth seeds which cause the colours of fiame to flash out.
